# cagit

take a repo with hundreds of thousands of commits (used git/git as example):
300MiB delta-compressed results in GBs of full history.

we want to be able to parse this as effeciently as possible.
this is where hash maps/sets become interesting.

example usage:

cargo build --release

# local
./target/release/cagit ~/h8d13/git commit -se "cat" oldest 1
bf0c6e839c692142784caf07b523cd69442e57a5  commit  Linus Torvalds: Make "cat-file" output the file contents to stdout.

# remote no clone needed
./target/release/cagit https://github.com/git/git.git commit -se "cat" oldest 1
HEAD 59ff4886a579f4bc91e976fe18590b9ae02c7a08
filter  tree:0
pack  33MiB
bf0c6e839c692142784caf07b523cd69442e57a5  commit  Linus Torvalds: Make "cat-file" output the file contents to stdout.

# earliest release (tag) whose history contains a commit. no clone.
./target/release/cagit https://github.com/git/git.git contains bf0c6e839c692142784caf07b523cd69442e57a5 -s
v0.99  a3eb250f996bf5e12376ec88622c4ccaabf20ea8  (gen 978)  Junio C Hamano: [PATCH] alternate object store and fsck

-s = summary
-e = exact word match, otherwise substring/regex
-a = (contains) list every containing tag, earliest first

the leanest partial-clone filter is negotiated automatically: commit-only queries
get filter=tree:0 (~300MiB → ~33MiB), tree queries get blob:none (~108MiB).
output is pipe-friendly (full sha40 + kind). use -s to add a one-line summary.

---

The difference with all the other git "search the index" tools:

Accepts both local file paths and remote URLs. No building local indexes. 
Not re-writing git or wrapping it. In memory/compute only no traces on disk.
(Only ever build cache DAG on /tmp for certain operations)
One sequential pass over the raw pack. Each object decompressed exactly once.
